## How can you adjust your communication style to be more inclusive of neurodivergent users and teammates?

I would focus on clear and concise communication, words and languages. I would also cosider reducing information and sensory overload, by making sure that I am not 
overwhelming them with alot of language and topics. I would also offer flexibility in terms of accomodating their needs, by checking in on them and asking about how they feel overall.

---

## What are some common UX or communication pitfalls that might make Focus Bear less accessible or supportive?

1) Monotone aesthetics: Whilst keeping a uniform colour scheme, the interface could potentially be unappealing to users - therefore, chances of unengagement is higher. 

2) Overwhelming interface: Initial onboarding process may seem overwhelming for neurodivergent users. The process may seem a little strict in terms of getting straight 
into routines and habits, rather than let them explore the settings and features first. 

3) Unclear onboarding process: this is relate to the overwhelming interface, where users have no clear support when figuring out how to use the app. 

---

## What is one practical change you can make in your work to better support vulnerable populations?

I would make sure there is a clear and concise onboarding process when users begin using Focus Bear. Allowing users to familiarise themselves with the app
and receiving guidelines would benefit neurodivergent users. Perhaps allow users to "demostrate" the functions like a game tutorial, before jumping straight into 
routines and other functions. 

